commit.message:
Support Ayatana AppIndicators

Ubuntu AppIndicator ([libappindicator]) was [removed in Debian Bullseye]
and has been superseded by Ayatana AppIndicator
([libayatana-appindicator]) for both [Debian] and [Ubuntu].

Add support for building with libayatana-appindicator instead of
libappindicator.

[libappindicator]: https://launchpad.net/libappindicator
[libayatana-appindicator]: https://github.com/AyatanaIndicators/libayatana-appindicator
[Debian]: https://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2018/03/msg00506.html
[Ubuntu]: https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/libayatana-appindicator/+bug/1915695
[removed in Debian Bullseye]: https://www.debian.org/releases/bullseye/amd64/release-notes/ch-information.en.html#noteworthy-obsolete-packages

Signed-off-by: Kevin Locke <kevin@kevinlocke.name>
Update configure.ac to make compatible with python3
README: Update to reflect my new PPA
1.0.1 Release
debian: Update maintainer and fix some linter warnings

debian: Add debian build files from webupd8

It appears that the Webupd8 PPA is defunct, so I think it makes
sense to pull the debian build files directly into the repo so that
anyone, possibly myself, can build new packages.

README: Update discussion around motivation

With Unity being deprecated, it's worth discussing the overall
desktop environment landscape and not be so Unity focused - this
plugin remains useful in GNOME and KDE.

README: Update discussion of secondary action

I've updated the README to clarify what the secondary action is and
how it gets triggered in different desktop environments.

I also finally decided to rename to README.md so my markdown actually
does something in github.

Remove unnecessary debug output from gtkdocklet code

Improves on original pull request by completely removing output,
which isn't required.

https://github.com/philipl/pidgin-indicator/pull/30

README: Point to official Fedora packages

Fedora now has official packaging and the unofficial repo appears
to be inactive.

README: Add discussion of click behaviour

A lot of people have asked why left-click does nothing in KDE, so I've added
some language to the README explaining that this is a KDE policy decision
and not something I have control over.

Implement proper blinking mechanism for indicator icon.

This was amusing. There's no way to get the icon to blink except
to alternate it between the regular icon and a 100% transparent
icon. And there's no such icon in the standard theme, so I had to
add one.
